          "body": "Verse 5 pivots from divine announcement to prophetic lament — the mode shifts from declaration to dirge. Baldness (shaving the head) and self-laceration (*gadad*, cutting oneself) were ancient Near Eastern mourning rites, proscribed for Israel (Deuteronomy 14:1) but practiced among surrounding peoples. Gaza shaves its head; Ashkelon falls silent (*damah*, to be struck dumb, to be silenced — the same root used for death-silence). The question addressed to the valley's remnant — 'How long will you gash yourself?' — is not a taunt but a lament. The prophet is not mocking the survivors but naming their grief as open-ended. No recovery oracle follows. Unlike the oracles against Moab (48:47), Ammon (49:6), or Elam (49:39), the Philistine oracle offers no eschatological restoration. The mourning of the remnant has no promised terminus. Then in verse 6 the lament turns from the survivors to the instrument of their destruction: 'Ah, sword of the Lord, how long will you not be quiet?' This apostrophe — addressing an inanimate weapon as a person — is one of Jeremiah's most dramatic prophetic devices, comparable only to his address to the land itself in chapter 4 (4:31). The cry 'how long' echoes the psalmic lament genre (Psalms 13:1; 74:10; 79:5; 94:3), and its appearance here suggests that even the prophet feels the weight of what he is announcing."
