        "number": 1,
        "title": "The historical superscription — prophecy anchored before the event",
        "range": "47:1",
        "excerpt": "That which came as the word of the Lord to Jeremiah the prophet concerning the Philistines, before Pharaoh conquered Gaza.",
        "body": "Verse 1 is a superscription — a formal heading that anchors the oracle in specific historical time before announcing its content. The phrase 'the word of the Lord came to Jeremiah' is the standard prophetic authorization formula (used over 50 times in Jeremiah alone), but its placement here before the OAN oracle signals that what follows is not Jeremiah's political analysis but divine disclosure. The prophet is the medium, not the author.\n\nThe chronological marker — 'before Pharaoh conquered Gaza' — is historically significant. Scholars have debated which Pharaoh is meant. The most probable identification is Pharaoh Necho II, whose northern campaigns in 609 BC followed the death of Josiah at Megiddo and who controlled the Levantine coast for several years before Nebuchadnezzar's decisive victory at Carchemish in 605 BC. An Egyptian military strike on Gaza is plausible in this context, and the archaeological record shows disruption at Gaza in this period. A minority view identifies Pharaoh Hophra and a later campaign.\n\nThe theological implication of the 'before' is what matters most: the oracle of Babylonian destruction was delivered before even the Egyptian assault on Gaza occurred. Jeremiah is not commenting on recent events or extrapolating from geopolitical trends. He is announcing what the Lord has determined before the intermediate events that might obscure it. Egypt's conquest of Gaza is the historical peg, but Babylon's flood is the divine purpose — and the prophet knows the divine purpose before the lesser event has unfolded.\n\nThis superscription also places Jeremiah 47 within the broader OAN collection whose editorial arrangement makes a canonical argument: the God who spoke to Jeremiah is the God who governs Egyptian armies (chapter 46), Babylonian campaigns (chapters 50-51), and every national power in between. The word came *to Jeremiah the prophet* — the title is not honorific but functional; it identifies the office through which divine word enters history.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davar YHWH* (word of the LORD) — the identical formula opens or governs most of Jeremiah's oracles; it is a claim about source, not style. *Terem* (before) — this preposition is rare in OAN superscriptions; its presence here specifically claims predictive priority for the oracle."
