        "body": "Verse 5 shifts mode abruptly from divine announcement to lament. The divine speech of verses 2-4 ends, and the prophet (or the text's poetic voice) surveys the aftermath in the language of mourning rites. The shaving of the head (*qorchah*, baldness) was the ancient Near Eastern practice of mourning over the dead, performed by stripping the scalp as a sign of grief. Leviticus 21:5 and Deuteronomy 14:1 prohibit it for Israel precisely because the nations practiced it — and here Jeremiah invokes it as the fitting image for Philistia's condition. Gaza is bald. Ashkelon is *damah* — silenced, struck dumb, reduced to the stillness of death.\n\nThe two cities stand as synecdoches for the whole Philistine pentapolis. Gaza, the southernmost and historically most contested city, was a gateway hub; Ashkelon, the coastal city slightly north, was a major port. Both laid low. The unnamed 'remnant of their valley' represents the survivors of the coastal plain still alive after the initial destruction — still practicing mourning, still gashing themselves in grief. The question 'how long will you gash yourself?' does not offer an answer. Unlike the lament psalms that move from 'how long' to divine response (Psalm 13), this question hangs in the text without resolution. The oracle of Jeremiah 47 contains no restoration promise for Philistia.\n\nThis absence is exegetically significant. Comparisons across Jeremiah's OAN reveal a deliberate pattern: Moab (48:47), Ammon (49:6), and Elam (49:39) each receive a brief eschatological restoration clause — 'yet I will restore the fortunes of Moab in the latter days.' Philistia receives no such clause. The 'how long' of verse 5 is left open, and it is not answered in verse 6 or 7 — only the sword's relentlessness is confirmed. This is consistent with the broader canonical treatment of Philistia: no restoration oracle exists for them in Isaiah, Ezekiel, or Amos either. The pattern of their judgment in Scripture is total and final.\n\nPeter Davids' observation in his work on lament literature applies here: the prophetic lament that lacks a response-clause is itself a form of judgment. The question 'how long' in the lament psalms typically precedes a declaration of trust or a divine oracle of answer. When neither comes — as here — the silence *is* the answer. There is no divine 'until,' no appointed end of mourning, because there is no appointed restoration. The text's silence at the end of verse 5 is not an omission; it is a verdict."
